description.plain:
“Scott Street” is one of a handful of songs Bridgers co-wrote with former flame (and current bandmate and drummer) Marshall Vore.

Bridgers has said in the past that the song is partly about her relationship with Vore, though when speaking with Song Exploder in 2019, the pair said the song is primarily about another relationship that Vore was in. In the interview, he described a past relationship that was “manipulative” in nature. While the theme of failed relationships is a focal point of the track, the song also explores the strangeness of reconnecting with people from our past.

The name of the real street is Scott Avenue and is located near Bedrock L.A. — a practice studio for bands and musicians in Los Angeles — and was often a place where Bridgers and Vore would spend time together while they were dating.

annotations: I’ve got a stack of mail and a tall can
In a podcast she says Marshall one day was walking outside to do something and was just singing everything that was happening hence the line “I’ve got a stack of mail and a tall can”
It’s a shower beer, it’s a payment plan

While “shower beer” is pretty self explanatory, it can be explained as a beer that is consumed while the consumer is taking a shower. Having a shower beer is a fairly redneck behavior, and Phoebe sometimes likes to poke fun at American traditions. There has been some research that suggests that drinking small amounts of alcohol while in the shower can actually boost your mood and make you more creative, so it’s possible that Phoebe, ever the subtle genius, is simply using shower beer as a metaphor for creativity.

Spending money and I earned it
 When I’m lonely, that’s when I’ll burn it

Consumerism makes working class people think they need to spend their money on things they don’t truly need. People often do this to fill the void or something lacking in their life, often referred to as “retail therapy”. Then, when they’ve depleted their funds, they must work for money to do it all again.

Phoebe is falling victim to this cycle here. Much like the drinking she mentions in the first verse, it’s a coping mechanism to numb the loneliness she feels instead of dealing with her emotions.
You said, “They’re all gettin’ married”
Also has been performed as You said, “They’re all having babies”

There’s helicopters over my head
 Every night when I go to bed
Scott Street is between Silverlake and Echo Park, a couple of blocks off Sunset Boulevard. Los Angeles Police and TV Station Helicopters are constantly flying around.
Said, “It’s too much shit to carry”

This response adds subtle humor to the conversation while furthering the idea that the drummer is refusing to play up to the nice “catch-up” talk. They’re giving straight, fairly pessimistic answers to the standard, how’s-it-been type questions Bridgers is asking.

I asked you, ”How is your sister?
 I heard she got her degree”

If the first two verses dictate the setting of a street Bridgers used to walk, these verses suggest a run-in on that street with an old friend. Bridgers brings us into the mood of the conversation quickly, setting the scene for an awkward catch-up talk. Bridgers asks the niceties, and gets vaguely bleak responses.
With an open heart, open container

“Open container” is law-enforcement shorthand for an unauthorized alcoholic drink open in public.

In this line, we learn that Bridgers' heart is exposed and sensitive but she doesn’t want it to be so and it probably rarely it is. Her sensitivity in this moment is suggested to be caused by the alcohol.

 It’s also a reference to the Elliott Smith song ‘St Ides Heaven’ from his second album. The opening lyrics to which are “Everything is exactly right / when I walk around here drunk every night / with an open container from 7/11 / in St Ides Heaven”
I asked you, “How is playing drums?”
This lyric is a subtle reference to Bridgers' former flame and current bandmate, Marshall Vore. Notably, the drums kick in right before this line is sung.

Anyway, don’t be a stranger (Ooh, ooh)
 Anyway, don’t be a stranger (Ooh, ooh)
 Don’t be a stranger (Ooh, ooh)

After a song full of meaningful but almost painfully numbed reflection, “don’t be a stranger” is thrown out repeatedly at the end, casually, almost as an afterthought. It reinforces the feeling that’s pushed throughout the whole song; how strange and uncanny it feels to run into someone who used to be a big part of your life.
The song also starts with Phoebe stating she feels like a stranger so it is ambiguous who this is referring to, the former lover or herself.

description.plain:
On “Motion Sickness,” Bridgers sings about how an older man has caused her distress in the form of what she describes as “emotional motion sickness,” explaining how he built her up and broke her heart — eventually leaving her behind.

During a live performance on NPR’s Tiny Desk series, Bridgers stated the meaning of the song:

[…] being in love with someone who is super mean to you… like conflicted feelings.

In a later performance on radio station KCRW, Bridgers revealed,

[“Motion Sickness”] was a song I wrote about Ryan Adams.

Ryan Adams recorded Bridgers' debut EP Killer in 2015.

In a 2019 article from The New York Times, Bridgers and other artists came forward and described Adams as physically, sexually, and emotionally abusive, noting that he used his influence as a popular musician to control young female collaborators and rising musicians.

annotations: You know I’m never gonna let you have it

I interpret this as “you know I will never let you have [the satisfaction of knowing that I miss you, who you once were, the best parts of the relationship, etc.]”

Further down in the song, Phoebe says she’s “try[ing] to stay clean and do without.” Codependent relationships can feel like an addiction to the people in them, especially to the partner with an anxious attachment style. The partner with the avoidant attachment style will often pull away in times of emotional turmoil, causing the anxious partner to feel as if they need to do whatever it takes to regain emotional closeness with the avoidant partner again. The anxious partner is often emotionally completely at the whim of the avoidant one. Avoidant partners also tend to be narcissistic people.

When relationships don’t end amicably, especially due to abuse or mistreatment, it’s not uncommon to cut off contact with your abuser, similar to that of quitting an addiction cold turkey. Phoebe is saying she is never going to let Ryan, her abuser, have the satisfaction of knowing that she misses him because she’s cut off contact with him, because she recognizes that their relationship was toxic, and because narcissists have the tendency to use similar vulnerability to manipulate
I guess it’s too late to change it now

Often, when people spend a lot of time together, particular features of another get on one’s nerves, even something as innocuous as an accent. What Bridgers may be referring to here, is the idea that there is no point in solving a problem that has gone on for too long. This line may be an allegory for her entire relationship: rather than trying to solve or change it, she has just given up.

There are no words in the English language
 I could scream to drown you out

Ryan Adam’s behavior follows her everywhere she goes, and it haunts her.

It’s also common of abusers to gaslight their victims, so that the victim of abuse will get angry, then feel like they’re the attacker because of that. She may be referencing how lots of his abuse is silent, and no matter how loud she screams, it’s still there.

I try to stay clean and live without
 And I wanna know what would happen
 If I surrender to the sound
 Surrender to the sound

In the final chorus, Bridgers invokes language used when people talk about addiction, saying she hopes to metaphorically “stay clean and live without” her ex and their toxic relationship. But the use of the word “try” and the fact that she compares being with her ex to an addictive substance implies that she has not completely moved past the relationship and, on some level, wants to go back to her ex. The end of this chorus confirms this, as she changes the lyrics from trying to drown out “the sound” of her ex to surrendering to that sound. After everything, she still thinks about getting back together with her ex and wonders if things would work out this time if they did.
I have emotional motion sickness

Ryan Adams, who is the real life person the song is about, had Ménière’s disease at the time. This is a condition whose symptoms are similar to those of motion sickness, including nausea, vomiting and difficulty maintaining balance. The medicine for motion sickness can reduce the severity of these symptoms.

Bridgers is saying that while Adams had actual motion sickness symptoms, the strains of their relationship felt like an emotional version of the same illness.

Also, the song uses fluctuating stereo panning, tremolo effects and subtle changes in speed, as if Bridgers wants the listener to experience their own motion sickness through the song.
But I will try to drown you out

This contrasts the earlier chorus, which says:

There are no words in the English language
I could scream to drown you out

This indicates growth and attempting to at least try to move past the pain, and drown out this awful person.

I’m on the outside looking through
 You’re throwing rocks around your room
 And while you’re bleeding on your back in the glass
 I’ll be glad that I made it out

This line references the idiom “Don’t throw stones in glass houses.” Now that she’s separated from her partner, she can see them clearly, as if through a pane of glass, and is able to recognize that their self-destructive behaviors made the relationship toxic.
Somebody roll the windows down

Motion sickness is common in cars. Windows on older cars were “rolled down” with a handle that you spun. Opening the window is felt to alleviate the symptoms of motion sickness and accompanying nausea.
Hey, why do you sing with an English accent?

From a 2003 NME review of a concert by Ryan Adams in Dublin:

Some fans however were left bemused by the New Yorker’s rather bizarre behaviour as he performed some songs in an English accent.

You gave me fifteen hundred
 To see your hypnotherapist
 I only went one time, you let it slide
 Fell on hard times a year ago
 Was hopin’ you would let it go and you did

Hypnotherapy is a form of alternative medicine in which a professional puts a patient into a trance-like state and makes suggestions that can alter patient’s bad behaviors. It is most often used to curb bad habits or rid a patient of stress.

In 2008, musician Ryan Adams announced that he was thinking of retiring from music because of his battle with Ménière’s disease. Throughout 2008-2014 he was on a bit of a hiatus from writing because of his struggle with this issue. Adams told Rolling Stone that he sought help from the use of medical marijuana as well as hypnotherapy.

Given past statements from Bridgers, it is likely that this line is in direct reference to Adams – who, it would seem, had directed Bridgers to see his hypnotherapist.

annotations: Ended up with a pair of cracked lips

The juxtaposition between a “creation myth” and “cracked lips” in this line and the one before it puts God and divine power in sharp contrast with the weakness and imperfection of the human experience to highlight the futility of Phoebe’s search for faith. This idea of questioning belief runs through the album, particularly strongly on “Chinese Satellite”.

Phoebe has described her relationship with religion as nonexistent.

Never had one, was not raised religious, atheist absolutely. I totally disagree with organized religion as a concept. That being said […] I think I was jealous of people with some sort of sense of greater community. And also people who could sleep at night, knowing that someone was taking care of them.

This line, then, expresses a frustration with religion and faith. In her search for God and something to believe in, Phoebe has come away with nothing more than cracked lips. This dryness of her lips could represent a thirst for knowledge or spiritual connection that remains unquenched.
No, I’m not afraid to disappear

In an interview with Genius, Phoebe explained that the song was about:

Just kind of being at peace with the end of the world. And I don’t mean in, like, an apathetic way. I just mean, like, instead of waking up every day during the apocalypse, like right now, and being heartbroken, you’re just kinda like, “Okay, what can I do today?” Like taking it kind of a day at a time instead of giving up.
Like a wave that crashed and melted on the shore

Here Phoebe alludes to Moon Song by  using water as metaphor for her relationship. Something she does many times in Moon Song I.E. “You’re holding me like water in your hands.”,
“You pushed me in and now my feet can’t touch the bottom of you”
“It’s nautical themed.”
And in Moon Song, Phoebe characterizes herself as innocent and arrogant. She refuses to acknowledge that their relationship is over and that this person doesn’t want her anymore. But in I Know the End her perspective on this changes. She accepts that their relationship is over and was never meant to last.

After a while, you went quiet
 And I got mean

Bridgers seems to react to (perceived) rejection by pushing the other person away — she tries to protect herself from getting hurt by hurting the other person first. She might also want to put to her lover’s feelings for them to the test and see if their partner loves them enough to endure bad treatment.

Phoebe has actually explained these lyrics in a November 2020 interview with Genius, saying:

When I get too close to people, I start to treat them like my parents, where you just say stuff to them that you even realize is in you. I just feel like, yeah, you don’t even really have to do that much to make up sometimes ‘cause both people wanna make up, but you know you’re being a dick and you don’t have to admit that you’re being a dick. You can just kind of float back into peace.

Windows down, scream along
 To some America First rap-country song

Phoebe is likely not referencing a specific song in this lyric but a very specific genre of music. The biggest sing-a-long rap country song of 2019 was undoubtedly “Old Town Road” by Lil Nas X, however it does not contain the “America First” mentality referenced in the line. A better example of this style could be the right-leaning track “Answer To No One” by Colt Ford. Republican presidential candidate Rick Perry even remixed the song in 2015 for his campaign.

In a November 2020 interview with Genius, Bridgers explained:

Pop-country radio has always been kind of close to my heart because my grandparents listened to it, my mom listens to it, but ever since the election, it’s made me realize— I mean, I think this is, like, the root of white privilege, where I’m like, “A lot of that stuff is racist!” Even though it’s so fucked up and even though that there is no place for me in the pop-country world, I know, like, a bunch of Toby Keith songs, and fuck Toby Keith, but when I’m alone in my car — trying to stay awake especially —, I’ll turn on pop-country and I’m like, “Oh, I actually do know all these lyrics.”

In Twitter, when asked about what song she was mentioning in this line, she wrote: “probably Sam Hunt or Jason Aldean”. It’s more likely she was singing Dirt Road Anthem or Take Your Time.

https://twitter.com/phoebe_bridgers/status/1326377096525062145
Big bolt of lightning hanging low

Lightning is the weapon of Zeus. The fact that it is “hanging low” depicts the surrealism of the world, as fantasy becomes dangerously close to intersecting reality. Perhaps society is so ruined that the gods themselves want to interfere.

Furthermore, the lightning could refer to heat lightning, which occurs silently in the summer. It builds upon Phoebe’s portrait of a very hot, intense environment: though there is no thundering, the atmosphere is stormy and foreboding.

This might also be a reference to the Space X launch she saw, which is mentioned in the next line.
Not even the burnouts are out here anymore

Phoebe refers to “burnouts,” or drug users that she often sees hanging around the beach. Burnouts are also often delinquents who don’t fit within societal norms, so it is extremely telling that even they have been affected by the apocalyptic events depicted in the song.

In an interview with Genius, Phoebe explained that:

The song is obviously a lot about the apocalypse, and I just thought of different subsets of people that would be affected by it. And the kids that hang out every day surfing, when they finally go…I feel like you really know that shit’s going down.

When I get back, I’ll lay around
 Then I’ll get up and lay back down
 Romanticize a quiet life

After returning home from touring, Phoebe isn’t sure what do with herself. “Get[ting] up and lay[ing] back down” implies a strong desire to do something, but the inability to do it. In an interview with Genius, Phoebe explained the feeling that these lines are meant to evoke:

When you’re on tour, at least I do this, like I’ll save recipes on Pinterest and I’ll decide I’m gonna garden now. I mean, I’ve been home for like over a year and I have no garden. I think it’s just that idea of romanticizing your life, and then when you get home, what you actually do is nothing compared to what you fantasized about.

The idea of a quiet garden life is also used in “Garden Song,” the second track on Punisher.

Drivin’ out into the sun
 Let the ultraviolet cover me up

In accordance with the apocalyptic narrative of this track, Phoebe is likely alluding to the destruction of the ozone layer. As the ozone layer depletes, greater amounts of harmful UV radiation can reach Earth’s surface.

In an interview with Genius, Phoebe explained the meaning behind these lyrics:

I want the hero’s journey to myself, or like, the origin story, but I’m super, super white and every time I go into the sun it’s just like poison. So I think driving out into the sun, and like Icarus shit…and then you just get scorched.
I’ll find a new place to be from

This line seems to be about disavowing your birthplace when it seems to be taking a path contrary to your own beliefs.

The lines preceding this talk about capitalism and greed, the hypocrisy of religion, the regressive “America First” movement, and paranoid conspiracy theories. This line is Phoebe saying that she refuses to associate with with these beliefs, and will no longer embrace her birth town/state/country as her home. She will instead choose to be “from” somewhere else.

It’s similar to the saying that “blood of the covenant is thicker than the water of the womb;” the relationships we choose to build and maintain are often stronger than the ones foisted on us by birth.

This line could also refer to an earlier line in this song about her not going down in a tornado with her hometown. If her hometown disappeared she would have to find a new place to be from.

description.plain:
“Kyoto” is an uptempo indie rock song that takes a glimpse into Bridgers' inner musings during her time spent on tour in Japan.

With a little help from Bright Eyes‘ Nathaniel Walcott on the horns, the song’s instrumentation sounds almost like joyful fanfare, despite some of the song’s lyrics of personal resentment. In an April 2020 press release, Bridgers described “Kyoto,” saying it was about her impostor syndrome.

In a May 2020 interview with The New Yorker, Bridgers reveals that the song also addresses the complex relationship she had with her father:

I feel so much fucking empathy and so much fucking anger toward him […] It’ll always be day to day: Are we talking, are we not talking? What’s the vibe?

In the midst of the 2020 COVID-19 pandemic, Bridgers stated she hoped to film the music video for “Kyoto” in Japan, but instead, filmed in front of a green screen. During the strict social-distancing policies held during the pandemic, Bridgers amusingly performed the song live from her bathtub on the late night show Jimmy Kimmel Live! in April 2020.

“Kyoto” is the second single to be released off her sophomore album Punisher.

annotations:
I don’t forgive you
 But please don’t hold me to it

This line, like the rest of the song, is in relation to Phoebe’s father’s drug addiction and domestic abuse. Phoebe doesn’t forgive him right now, but this line may be hinting that one day she might. In an interview, she talks about the conflicting emotions of having so much anger and empathy towards him and in this line, in particular, is talking about these conflicting feelings. It seems as if Phoebe might one day want to forgive him but at the time she was writing this song, she couldn’t do it.
[Chorus]

In an interview with MSNBC, Phoebe explained the lyrics to this chorus:

That’s a lyric about my dad. My brother and I had a very complex childhood, but I think one of the shortest-term feelings for me is anger, so just writing about that feeling— My friend Christian has a lyric about this, like, I’m trying really hard to be angry, and if I relax for a second, I might forgive. […] I think I don’t know a single person that doesn’t have a complex relationship with one or both of their parents. I don’t trust people who have a perfect relationship with both their parents. One of my favourite things about writing with truth is when people come up to you and talk about almost the same exact experience that you’ve had, which is such a weird thing, so cool.

Sunset’s been a freak show
 On the weekend, so
This may be in reference to Sunset Boulevard, a major street in Los Angeles, Phoebe’s hometown.
To park at the Goodwill

Goodwill is a thrift store with affordable prices for clothing and many other items. Bridgers is a successful musician with a net worth of 1.5 million, so going to Goodwill might be harkening to a time when she was less successful. This entire song is about processing her childhood, so it would make sense for her to harken to the past in this way.
I wanted to go, but I didn’t

This line seems to be describing the specific feeling of when you want to go out and have fun with your friends but you’re stuck in your own head and would rather wallow in your pain. Her band went to the arcade and she wanted to go with them, but she didn’t.

It could also be that she wanted to go with the band but then the subject of the song (her father) called her so she had to stay back and answer the call.

To tell me you’re getting sober
 And you wrote me a letter

A reference to her abusive father, he likely tried to get back into her life by telling her he’s sober now or he’s changed but she’s hesitant to believe it. This may not be true, as abusive people will lie and manipulate others to get what they want.

Step nine of the Alcoholics Anonymous Big Book of recovery is making “amends for emotional harm done.” This may be a reference to the practice of letter writing around this step of the recovery practice and about how an alcoholic should ask for forgiveness but not expect to receive it.

Guess I lied
 I’m a liar
 Who lies
 ’Cause I’m a liar

The outro ultimately sums up her feelings towards her father; that her hatred of him was a lie, and also that her forgiveness of him was a lie.

She contradicts herself on just about every line concerning her father and she carries that onto the outro. Every piece of hate she had for her father is a lie (because she’s a liar) but every piece of love she had was also a lie.

You called me from a payphone
 They still got payphones
 It cost a dollar a minute
Bridgers told Rolling Stone that she “totally made up” the lyric “You called me from a payphone, they still got payphones, it cost a dollar a minute” and “never even Googled it.”
But I don’t have to read it

People in recovery from addiction are often torn about making amends to people they have hurt without hurting them further through the process of making amends. (This is expressed in the 9th step of the Twelve Step program: “Made direct amends to such people wherever possible, except when to do so would injure them or others.”) One way this can be expressed is for someone to write a letter of amends but then tell the recipient they don’t have to read it. The writer may feel that this is avoiding the problem of creating additional emotional labour by giving the recipient the choice to read it or not. However, this does still create emotional labour for the recipient who has to think and feel about the fact that the letter exists, whether to read it, how to respond to the “you don’t have to read it.”

I wanted to see the world
 Then I flew over the ocean
 And I changed my mind (Woo)

A song that has been proven to be about her relationship with her father, this lyric is the pinnacle of that connection to me. Bridgers states that she has always dreamed about seeing the world, as every child wishes. She believes that the physical act of taking herself away from home was self driven and no outside motivation, However, Bridgers quickly realises that this isn’t the truth the minute she finds herself overseas. She finds out that the true reason she wanted to get away was because of her abusive and drug addict father. She has “changed her mind” and no longer wants to “see the world”. She wants to be away from trauma.




Wanting to see the world (go many places) seems like an idyllic goal to have, but they don’t talk about the bigger, more boring parts of the journey.

While “seeing the world” is generally figurative in meaning, Phoebe here plays off a literal interpretation of the phrase to evoke the image of a person actually trying to look at every place on the planet, but not realizing that “every place” includes enormous stretches of unchanging, monolithic ocean.

This, of course, is a metaphor for how touring and other things she thought would be fun and exhilarating didn’t live up to her expectations as experiences.

This song is about being on tour and hating tour, and then being home and hating home. I just always want to be where I’m not, which I think is pretty not special of a thought, but it is true. With ​boygenius, we took a red-eye to play a late-night TV show, which sounds glamorous, but really it was hurrying up and then waiting in a fucking backstage for like hours and being really nervous and talking to strangers. I remember being like, “This is amazing and horrible at the same time. I’m with my friends, but we’re all miserable. We feel so lucky and so spoiled and also shitty for complaining about how tired we are.

– Apple Music

Additionally, the metaphor is very loose-fitting, and while it has a specific meaning in this case, it can easily be expanded to just simply be a metaphor for something that seemed exciting but ended up mostly boring, or even just for things in general that didn’t live up to expectations.

These lines also seem as veiled references to the myth of Icarus and Daedalus, tying into the second theme of the song, Phoebe’s relationship with her own father. Icarus' “want to see the world” is inspired by his father’s invention of wax wings. His ability to see the world rested in the faith he held in Daedalus' invention, alluding to Phoebe’s naive faith and trust in her own father. Both Phoebe and Icarus flew over the ocean. As Icarus escaped from Crete with his wings, Daedalus reminded him not to fly too high lest he melt the wax binding the wings together. Awed by the new perspective, he began to fly too high despite his father’s warning, causing him to fall to his ultimate demise. While Phoebe flies over the ocean in a plane, her travel to Japan similarly changed her mind to disregard her father.

annotations: And I’ve never seen you smiling so big

Bridgers sings that she sees her lover smiling big only in dreams. The rest of the song, they are fighting over musicians until she cries or he’s crying over a little bird. Her wanting to give her lover the moon is a huge and impossible thing, and even something as simple as a smile is only possible in dreams now.

And there’s something I’m supposed to say
 But can’t for the life of me
 Remember what it is

Although Phoebe wants to be able to say the right thing, the level of disconnect that she is feeling from her life is stopping her from being able to do this. She is going through the motions without really being present, realising that there is an appropriate reaction to the situation, but is unable to have a genuine emotional response as she is mentally too far detached from her body. This emotional disconnect is common for people suffering from depression or other mental health problems.
And then went to bed upset

The advice to “not go to bed angry” with your partner(s) is common. According to Psychology Today, this advice has some scientific backing–people report higher levels of sleep disruption the morning after conflict. Bridgers might be referencing this common advice when she says she’s going to bed upset.
Until I cried

John lennon has admitted to being a perpetrator of being an absent father, as well as one that inflicts acts of domestic violence, much like Phoebe’s own father.

Here’s an article about John Lennon:
https://www.vice.com/en/article/ypa9b5/you-dont-have-to-imagine-john-lennon-beat-women-and-childrenits-just-a-fact

Phoebe says here that her father inflicted “textbook domestic abuse:
https://www.thefader.com/2018/09/06/phoebe-bridgers-cover-story-interview

It’s also alluded to that her father wasn’t very present in her life in “Kyoto”:
https://genius.com/19950584

Thus, I think that Phoebe might be processing her own abuse through John Lennon somehow. Her partner is saying that she deserves better, but she has a hard time accepting this, and wants to cling onto her past and/or cannot get rid of her adoration. Because of this, her love, “the dead little bird”, becomes mangled and, well, dead, due to spending so much energy on toxin.
But you’re holding me like water in your hands

Phoebe utilizes the metaphor of water to describe how people, like water, are delicate to hold because they can slip away any moment if you aren’t careful; relationships are fragile.

This line returns the song to its recurring water imagery, for example:

And you pushed me in
And now my feet can’t touch the bottom of you

and

And you’re singing at my birthday
[…]
It’s nautical themed

The metaphor of water is especially significant considering the title of the track, “Moon Song.” The moon is known to control the tides, making them rise and fall, perhaps similarly to this tumultuous relationship.

Water is also not easily held in your hands, and often drips and leaks out. This could be a metaphor referring to the lack of effort Phoebe feels from her partner: she is giving her all to make sure he feels content while his methods of support, or lack thereof, are leaving her feeling badly. Just like water drips out of your hands, Phoebe feels that the “help” her partner is giving her is causing her to lose pieces of herself.

And if I could give you the moon
 I would give you the moon

In an interview with MSNBC, Phoebe revealed that this was, at the time, her favourite lyric she has ever written.

The name “Phoebe” is a latinized form of the Greek name “Phoibe,” the name of a Greek Titan associated with the moon. Phoebe would give this person all of herself.

This also may have been inspired from from a quote in the famous Christmas movie, It’s a Wonderful Life (1946). George Bailey says:

What do you want, Mary? Do you want the moon? If you want it, I’ll throw a lasso around it and pull it down for you. Hey! That’s a pretty good idea! I’ll give you the moon, Mary.

She shows that she is willing to move heaven and earth in order to give them the moon, to please him — she is desperately putting everything into their relationship and is willing to meet their every need no matter how impossible it might seem.

But now I am dreaming
 And you’re singing at my birthday

Since “Moon Song” is ostensibly addressed to Conor Oberst, Phoebe’s collaborator and bandmate from Better Oblivion Community Center, this line could be a reference to “At the Bottom of Everything”, the opening track to the 2005 album I’m Wide Awake, It’s Morning by Conor’s main band Bright Eyes.

In the song’s intro, Conor tells the surreal story of two passengers, a man and a woman, on a plane that suddenly breaks and is heading towards the ocean. As the plane falls, the man tells the woman that they are going to her birthday party and begins to hum a tune. Phoebe’s dream has a similar series of events, albeit not on a falling plane but at her actual birthday party. In this scenario, Conor is the man in the story singing to the other passenger, Phoebe. This allusion is further reinforced by the fact that Phoebe’s birthday is nautical themed, resembling the ocean from the story.

You asked to walk me home
 But I had to carry you

In a literal sense, Bridgers is describing a time when her partner was intoxicated after a night out together and she ended up being responsible for them, even though they said they would take care of her.

A second, more metaphorical, meaning can be applied here as well. Bridgers could be saying her partner wanted to be the caregiver in their relationship, but ended up being too emotionally drained. The partner couldn’t even “walk [her] home”, but rather Bridgers was the one who had to carry the weight of both of them.

In pop culture, a boy walking a girl home usually means that he feels protective over her and doesn’t want her to get hurt on the way home, and that is what Phoebe’s partner is trying to express to her, though they can’t deliver.

You are sick and you’re married
 And you might be dying

A possible nod to Conor Oberst, who, in 2016, was diagnosed with a cyst on his brain. While brain cysts aren’t necessarily deadly, they’re extremely painful. Oberst married Corina Figueroa Escamilla in 2010 (the couple has since separated), but had nodded to being in an open relationship several times. Interesting to note that Bright Eyes, a band fronted by Oberst, has an unreleased song titled “Comet Song”, as well.

This could also be a reference to the 2008 Charlie Kaufman film, Synecdoche New York, in which the main character, Caden, says while lying next to his mistress, “I’m really, uh–I’m really sick. And I think I’m dying. I have a kid, and I’m married.”
You couldn’t have, you couldn’t have

The violent imagery of the kiss directly contrasts with, and exaggerates, the genuine love Phoebe has for the subject of the song. Furthermore, it highlights the inequity in the relationship, and Phoebe’s role as a metaphorical doormat, happy simply to please her love interest while being treated with little respect.

There could also be a double meaning. Phoebe being in denial, saying that they couldn’t have kissed someone else, and she wont or can’t believe it. 2On the other hand, she could be stating that they couldn’t have kissed someone who loves you more, because she loves them the most.

And it’s 4AM again
 And I’m doing nothing
 Again

This being the outro suggests that she may have reflected on death and depression but that she is doing nothing to change her attitude towards these ideas. She will be doing nothing to address her mental health again and again.
I have a friend I call

The friend is Harrison Whitford, Phoebe’s guitarist. Prior to playing “Funeral” at Charlotte Metro Credit Union on September 18, 2021 Phoebe explained that he is the friend mentioned. She stated that they were both depressed and that being depressed together often helped them both (“and then we laughed until it disappeared”).

And that’s just how I feel
 Always have and I always will
 I always have and always will

When people feel sad and especially when people are experiencing symptoms of depression it’s common to feel like that’s the way things have always been. That sadness and depression has always been present. Worse it feels like that sadness will always be there.

The chorus is especially powerful because of the structure and pauses. They make you feel the sadness for that much longer. “I’m so blue” [quick pause] “all the time” [quick pause] “and that’s just how I feel” [quick pause] “Always have” [quick pause] “and I always will”. Each line following a pause adds to that feeling of never-ending and ever-present sadness.

And last night, I blacked out in my car
 And I woke up in my childhood bed

The line about blacking out could be mentioning dissociation, an experience of “zoning out” or disconnecting from your thoughts and feelings, and even your physical body. Dissociation is a common symptom of trauma, and can be a trauma response in those with PTSD.
Phoebe dissociates and ends up in the house she grew up in, possibly a subconscious emotional response to the sadness she feels for the family of the boy who’s funeral she’s singing at.
But then we laugh until it disappears

Despite the fact that they talk until they feel all the pain and the anxiety from death and the thought of it, they still are happy people. The joys of life can get them past thinking about death. Live in the moment essentially.

Or, darker, maybe they laugh to ignore the pains and tribulations of death. Instead of finding true happiness they create falsified happiness. This is potentially more likely because the next verse talks about how she passed out, and she could be very very depressed.

And I don’t need you to tell me what that means
 I don’t believe in that stuff anymore

This line perhaps juxtaposes the innocence felt in the previous verse, when Bridgers sings of “a kid a year older than [herself].” The aforementioned verse presents the singer as someone youthful, which is often commensurable with credulity and a rudimentary outlook on life.

Instead, she rejects the superstitious and Freudian beliefs in what a dream could mean, losing a sense of childlike wonder, perhaps, something often exhibited by individuals in a depressive episode, which the song in its entirety heavily alludes to.
For a kid a year older than me

The juxtaposition of the words “a kid” and “older than me” show that Phoebe is, well, young.

Normally, if you’re calling someone a “kid” you mean they’re younger than you, but here Phoebe follows up the phrasing of “a kid” immediately by saying they’re a year older than her. She’s effectively saying she’s younger than a kid, highlighting the youth of both Phoebe and the person whose funeral it is. It could also imply she feels older than her actual age.
Jesus Christ, I’m so blue all the time

The use of “Jesus Christ” in the chorus is interesting when taken in context. In the first chorus, it follows the line “I don’t believe in that stuff anymore.” This suggests that in addition to dream interpretations, religion is something that no longer provides intrinsic meaning to Phoebe. In the second chorus, it follows the line “Someone’s kid is dead.” In Christianity, Jesus is the Son of God who was killed for our sins. Perhaps in the face of this tragedy, Phoebe can see (even if she does not believe) how Christian belief could be comforting to others who see God as having experienced their grief.

And I have this dream where I’m screamin’ underwater
 While my friends are all waving from the shore

This dream she is having could be interpreted in many ways by people who interpret dreams. Why are none of her friends saving her? Maybe it is an analogy for her sadness, that she feels alone in her suffering and feels as though her friends cannot help her out of it. As she explains in the next line, however, she does not believe in interpreting the content of dreams anymore. Her detailing this specific dream in the song does, however, raise the possibility that a part of her finds her dreams, or at least this one, significant in some way.
When I think too much about it, I can’t breathe
Panic from thinking about difficult or anxiety-inducing topics such as death could make it harder to breathe

annotations: Crocodile tears,

“Crocodile tears is a false, insincere display of emotion such as a hypocrite crying fake tears of grief. The phrase derives from an ancient belief that crocodiles shed tears while consuming their prey, and as such is present in many modern languages, especially in Europe where it was introduced through Latin.” – Wikipedia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crocodile_tears)
Emotional affair

When she says that it’s an “emotional affair”, she alludes to the idea of her partner having a close relationship with someone else, and investing much more time, energy, and feelings with the other. This, along with the other lyrics, clearly point to a toxic relationship between her and her partner.
All the bad dreams that you hide

This could allude back to the previous lines about drowning in one’s sleep. Phoebe knows that her partner has baggage, but her partner seems unwilling to express it – hence, drowning in their ‘sleep.’ This is a a metaphor for one’s inability to fluidly express themselves and their emotions. Phoebe wants her partner to open up to her so that she can, in return, provide reassurance for the sake of their relationship. Thematically, this aligns with the concept of a ‘savior complex.’

All the skeletons you hide
 Show me yours and I’ll show you mine
Over Twitter, Phoebe explained that this lyric is referencing “secrets and nudes”, showing the physical and emotional intimacy between the subject and Phoebe.

One hand on the wheel, one in your mouth
 Turn me on and turn me down

Phoebe stated on Twitter that this line is about ‘picking someone up from the airport and the horny drive home before you have sex’

https://twitter.com/phoebe_bridgers/status/1326384458224840704?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw
Overly sincere

Codependents are often incredible people pleasers.

Growing up with a chemically dependent guardian (or sibling), typically with unpredictable behavior, you learn to anticipate the needs and emotions of others for survival. Phoebe has stated that her dad was an alcoholic.

Often when one parent is chemically dependent, the other parent is codependent (in the case there are 2 guardians). Codependents hold a lot of resentment and can be just as unpredictable as the chemically dependent guardian. Often bursting into rage fits.

As a child you aren’t capable of discerning what is happening and the message you receive is that you’re not lovable enough and something is wrong with you. This creates a deep wound, where you try to prove your worthiness by surrendering to the needs of others and often abandon yourself.

When you grow up in this environment, you learn to “please” others quickly. And paired with a deep wound in terms of self-worth and lovableness, you begin to need the validation you receive from others when you please them.
Run the tap ’til it’s clear

“Run the tap ‘til it’s clear” refers to turning on a faucet for the first time in a long time, where the water’s initially brown with rust and calcium and sediments that have built up over time. So you have to run the tap for a while to get the crap out. Here, Bridgers is using this image to reflect the way old junk gets released with emotional openness and honesty she’s calling for.

Baby, you’re a vampire
 You want blood and I promised
 I’m a bad liar

This verse is a reference to Phoebe’s partner (or the partner of the person singing) sucking the life out of the singer. In these four lines, Phoebe lays both of their problems out in the open, in hopes of reconciliation.

“I’m a bad liar” may refer to the end of Kyoto.
Show me yours, I’ll show you mine

Phoebe is using the expression “show me yours, I’ll show you mine” in a literal sense, to describe the physical intimacy and nudity shared by partners and in a metaphorical sense, to describe the reciprocal need for partners to air emotional baggage without fear of judgement or shame coming between them.

Phoebe herself said this line was about “secrets, and nudes” when asked about its meaning on her Twitter account.

Wake up and start a big fire
 In our one room apartment
 But I’m too tired
 To have a pissing contest

“Wake up and start a big fire / In our one room apartment” most likely refers to PB’s partner picking fights/creating a volatile environment that is inescapable, due to living in such a small space together. “But I’m too tired / To have a pissing contest” means both that she’s too tired to throw insults back & forth / fight pettily, AKA a “pissing contest”, as well as, more metaphorically, she’s too exhausted to “extinguish the fire” her partner has set.

Something in the water means that  there are so many people or things doing a particular thing or having a certain trait. She was not taller before, and now she is, because she grew up quicker then she realized.

Someday, I’m gonna live
 In your house up on the hill
A possible nod to Elliott Smith’s posthumous record “From a Basement on the Hill”, introducing the overall album theme of Bridgers' infatuation with the singer/songwriter.
I don’t know how, but I’m taller

ties together the whole theme of growing up in this song. it starts with a childhood home burning down, then being a rebellious teenager, then being in college and wanting to have sex. The speakers growth is also paralleled with the growth of her garden, and while she isn’t sure why she’s still growing she knows the garden is growing for a dark reason. this furthers the theme in this song of growing through difficult things and having a happy life, as stated in the last lines
I don’t know when you got taller

The entire song seems to be about growing up, and Phoebe uses the motif of getting taller to act as a metaphor for becoming more emotionally mature.

In this chorus, she talks about a relative growing up, and this is contrasted in the second chorus when she switches to singing about herself growing up. She also reminisces about when she was younger, and possibly more innocent. As she grew older, she saw this person leave her and so they are taller when she sees them again.

And when I grow up, I’m gonna look up
 From my phone and see my life

References the stereotypical Gen Z feeling of spending so much time on your phone that you feel like you’re living vicariously through other people on social media.
Bridgers could be saying that she hopes this is a habit she’ll grow out of as she gets older. Possibly in the hope that the life she ‘looks up’ at will be better and more fulfilling than the one on her phone.

Additionally, this line seems to call back to the expression that life can pass you by quickly if you’re distracted and not paying attention, which is reminiscent of the themes of growing up present throughout this song.

And when I find you
 You touch my leg and I insist
 But I wake up before we do it

In a June 2020 Playboy interview, Bridgers explains why these lines, in particular, are one of the rare instances of love and romance presented on the album Punisher:

I think love has really been a changing form for me in my adulthood. There isn’t as much of a script for friendship, so I think the lines kind of blur on the record between romance and platonic friendship. They’re kind of becoming the same thing to me. Sometimes I’ll be like, ‘I’m going to write a song about my friend,’ and then I end up with this very obvious Starbucks love song. […] I don’t know, like a Jason Mraz song. My corniest songs that are the least fraught are about my friends.
Then it’s a dorm room, like a hedge maze

In dreams the dreamer often experiences a characteristically sudden shift in “setting.”

The use of a garden as a symbol for sexual awakening or for the female body is classic, although the hedge maze lends an air of danger or uncertainty to this metaphor.

It certainly evokes the difficulty and confusion of young adults trying to find their way around one anothers' bodies for the first time.

I hopped the fence when I was seventeen
 Then I knew what I wanted

The Huntington is a private botanical garden in Pasadena, near where she lives.   Here, she has hopped the fence as a teen (along with the person she is singing to) and together they’ve looked at their reflections.

The reflection of the two of them together tells the narrator (at 17) what she wants out of life.  It implies that one of those things is the relationship, which is the most straightforward view; but it may also indicate a desire for clear vision of herself, for shared experiences of transgressive behavior (e.g. sneaking into a garden), or for the two of them to be united in a beautiful natural setting.

Perhaps this line also touches on human tendency to feel like we know exactly what we want as teens, while adulthood can bring more ambivalence.

I grew up here ’til it all went up in flames

Phoebe is from Pasadena, California and alludes to different aspects of her hometown throughout the song.

Providing insight on these lyrics, The New Yorker writes, ”When Bridgers was twenty, her parents divorced. The year before, their house had caught fire. ‘The metaphor is insane,” she said, laughing. “Their breakup was horrible. Really, really vindictive and shitty. Laying down on the lawn
 I’m tired of trying to get in the house

These two lines possibly allude “Christina’s World,” the famous 1948 painting by American painter Andrew Wyeth. In the painting, Christina Olson lies in the grass and facing toward the farmhouse. She was afflicted by a degenerative muscle condition, thus the painting likely depicts her struggle of trying to crawl the long distance back to the farmhouse.
Bridgers is also concerned with artwork later in the song, and in the second verse sings, “If you’re a work of art / I’m standing too close.”

For Bridgers, this distance is not a physical one but an emotional one. These lines express Bridgers' discontent and frustration at having to navigate her complex emotions yet again. In this case, given the context of the following lines, the end goal is content and a permanence positive feeling, rather than believing “whenever [she] feel[s] good, it’ll be the last time.”

There’s such a thing as spending too much time with a person. Their flaws become obvious and they can start to become annoying. The juxtaposition of seeing the “brush strokes” and voicing her grievances with his mom means that in this case, the things her ex has inherited from his parents are particularly annoying. She’s started to notice traces of the things she hates about his mom in Marshall himself.
